Object.assign(QUESTIONS,{

"g8-06": [
  // Easy (Q1–4)
  {q:"Which of the following is an ABIOTIC component of a rainforest ecosystem?",
   opts:["A jaguar","Rainfall","A bromeliad plant","Leaf-cutter ants"],c:1,
   e:"Abiotic components are non-living parts of an ecosystem. Rainfall is a non-living, physical factor. Jaguars, bromeliads and leaf-cutter ants are all biotic (living) components."},

  {q:"In which layer of the tropical rainforest would you find the most biodiversity?",
   opts:["Forest floor","Emergent layer","Canopy layer","Understorey"],c:2,
   e:"The canopy layer, at roughly 20–40 metres, receives the most sunlight and is the most densely vegetated. It therefore supports the greatest number of animal and plant species. The forest floor receives less than 2% of sunlight, making it far less productive."},

  {q:"Why do tropical rainforests receive high rainfall throughout the year?",
   opts:["They are located at the poles where cold air rises","Convectional rainfall occurs because intense solar heating causes warm, moist air to rise rapidly, cool, and condense","They are near cold ocean currents that bring moisture","Trade winds blow rain in from the desert"],c:1,
   e:"Tropical rainforests lie near the Equator. Intense solar heating causes warm, moist air to rise rapidly (convection), cool, and condense as heavy rainfall — often as afternoon thunderstorms. This pattern repeats daily, giving the rainforest its high, year-round rainfall (over 2,000 mm/year)."},

  {q:"What is deforestation?",
   opts:["The planting of new trees in a cleared area","The permanent removal of forests to use the land for other purposes","The slow death of trees due to disease","The movement of animals out of the rainforest"],c:1,
   e:"Deforestation is the permanent removal or clearing of forests, typically to make way for agriculture, logging, mining or urban development. It is 'permanent' because the land is converted and not replanted — distinguishing it from selective logging where the forest recovers."},

  // Medium (Q5–8)
  {q:"Why is the soil beneath a tropical rainforest actually poor in nutrients despite the enormous amount of vegetation?",
   opts:["The soil is too sandy to hold nutrients","Heavy rainfall leaches nutrients deep into the ground, and most nutrients are stored in the living biomass rather than the soil","The trees deliberately prevent nutrients from entering the soil","Cold temperatures slow down decomposition"],c:1,
   e:"Nutrient cycling in the rainforest is extremely rapid. Nutrients from decomposing leaf litter are almost immediately absorbed by shallow tree roots before they can accumulate in the soil. Heavy rainfall also leaches (washes) minerals downward. When the forest is cleared, this fragile cycle breaks and the exposed soil quickly becomes infertile."},

  {q:"Which of the following is a HUMAN cause of deforestation in the Amazon rainforest?",
   opts:["A volcanic eruption burying trees under ash","Lightning strikes causing wildfires","Cattle ranching — land is cleared to create pasture for beef production","Natural flooding drowning trees along river banks"],c:2,
   e:"Cattle ranching is the leading human cause of Amazon deforestation. Large areas are cleared to create pasture. Other human causes include soya farming, logging, mining and road-building. Volcanic eruptions, lightning fires and flooding are natural events, not human activities."},

  {q:"What does ecotourism offer as a strategy for sustainable rainforest management?",
   opts:["It allows unrestricted tourist access to all forest areas to raise maximum income","It replaces the forest with tourist resorts","It provides income for local communities from tourists visiting the natural environment, giving people an economic reason to protect the forest","It involves paying loggers to plant one new tree for every one they cut down"],c:2,
   e:"Ecotourism generates income for local communities from tourists who come to experience the natural forest. Because local people benefit financially from the forest remaining intact, they have an economic incentive to protect it rather than clear it. This sustainable approach links conservation with development."},

  {q:"Approximately what percentage of Earth's plant and animal species are found in tropical rainforests, even though rainforests cover only about 6% of the land surface?",
   opts:["About 10%","About 25%","Over 50%","Less than 5%"],c:2,
   e:"Tropical rainforests are the most biodiverse ecosystems on Earth, home to more than 50% of the world's species despite covering only approximately 6% of the land surface. This is because the warm, wet, stable climate and complex multi-layered structure provide a huge range of ecological niches."},

  // Hard (Q9–10)
  {q:"A farmer in Brazil clears 50 hectares of rainforest to grow soya. After three years the yields fall dramatically. Which geographical explanation best accounts for this?",
   opts:["The farmer used the wrong type of soya seeds","Rapid nutrient cycling means nutrients are held in the biomass; once the forest is removed and crops harvested, nutrients are not returned and the soil quickly becomes exhausted","The rainforest soil was too deep for soya roots to reach water","Increased rainfall after clearing washes away the crops"],c:1,
   e:"In a rainforest, nutrients cycle rapidly through the biomass. When the forest is cleared and crops are grown, harvesting the crops removes nutrients from the system. Without the rapid decomposition of leaf litter returning nutrients, the naturally nutrient-poor soil is quickly exhausted — a process known as soil degradation. This is a major long-term consequence of deforestation."},

  {q:"Evaluate the effectiveness of debt-for-nature swaps as a rainforest management strategy.",
   opts:["They are ineffective because they cost nothing","They are highly effective because they give poor countries money to plant new trees wherever they choose","They can be effective because a country's foreign debt is cancelled in exchange for legally protecting rainforest, reducing financial pressure to exploit the forest — but success depends on effective enforcement and governance","They work only in wealthy countries with no debt"],c:2,
   e:"Debt-for-nature swaps cancel a developing country's debt to a wealthier nation or bank in exchange for a legally binding commitment to protect a designated area of rainforest. This removes the financial pressure that often drives deforestation. However, the strategy's success depends on strong governance and effective enforcement on the ground — without these, protected areas may still be illegally cleared."}
],

"g8-07": [
  // Easy (Q1–4)
  {q:"What annual rainfall level defines a hot desert?",
   opts:["Less than 1,000 mm","Less than 500 mm","Less than 250 mm","Less than 2,500 mm"],c:2,
   e:"Hot deserts are defined as areas receiving less than 250 mm of rainfall per year. Many receive far less — the Atacama Desert in Chile averages less than 1 mm per year in some areas. This extreme aridity shapes all other characteristics of desert environments."},

  {q:"Why do desert temperatures drop dramatically at night?",
   opts:["Cold ocean currents blow in during the evening","There is no cloud cover to trap the heat radiated from the ground","Desert sand absorbs heat from the atmosphere at night","Strong winds cool the surface rapidly in all deserts"],c:1,
   e:"Deserts have very little water vapour or cloud cover. During the day, clear skies allow intense solar radiation to heat the ground. At night, without clouds to act as an insulating blanket and trap outgoing longwave radiation, heat escapes rapidly into the atmosphere, causing temperatures to plummet — sometimes below freezing."},

  {q:"Which adaptation helps a cactus survive with very little water?",
   opts:["Broad, flat leaves to absorb maximum rainfall","A shallow root system concentrated directly under the stem","Fleshy stems that store water, and leaves reduced to spines to minimise water loss","Bright coloured flowers that attract rain clouds"],c:2,
   e:"Cacti (xerophytes) store water in their fleshy stems and reduce water loss by having leaves modified into spines, which present a tiny surface area for transpiration. A broad root system maximises collection of any rainfall. These are classic plant adaptations to an arid environment."},

  {q:"In which latitudinal belt are most hot deserts found?",
   opts:["0–5° North and South of the Equator","5–15° North and South of the Equator","15–35° North and South of the Equator","60–80° North and South of the Equator"],c:2,
   e:"Hot deserts are predominantly found between 15° and 35° North and South of the Equator. This is where the Hadley Cell creates a belt of descending, dry air (subtropical high pressure) that inhibits rainfall. This explains the location of the Sahara, Arabian, Sonoran and Australian deserts."},

  // Medium (Q5–8)
  {q:"What is desertification?",
   opts:["The natural expansion of a desert into previously uninhabited areas","The conversion of fertile or semi-arid land into unproductive, desert-like conditions, primarily driven by human activities and drought","The deliberate irrigation of desert land to make it fertile","The planting of trees in desert areas to create new ecosystems"],c:1,
   e:"Desertification is the degradation of land in arid, semi-arid and dry sub-humid areas. It turns productive land at the desert's edge into unproductive, desert-like terrain. Human activities such as overgrazing, deforestation and over-cultivation are major drivers, often in combination with prolonged drought."},

  {q:"A wadi is a characteristic desert landform. What is a wadi?",
   opts:["A large, crescent-shaped sand dune","A flat-topped, isolated rock formation","A dry river channel that fills suddenly during rare intense rainfall events","A type of desert oasis fed by underground springs"],c:2,
   e:"A wadi is a dry river channel (valley) that normally contains no water. During infrequent but intense rainstorms, wadis can fill rapidly and violently with flash floods. They are a common landform in the Sahara and Arabian deserts. The sudden flooding makes them hazardous for travellers and settlers."},

  {q:"Which of the following is a human cause of desertification in the Sahel region of Africa?",
   opts:["A sudden cooling of the Indian Ocean","A shift in Earth's orbit away from the Sun","Overgrazing by livestock, which strips vegetation and exposes fragile soil to wind erosion","The northward movement of the African tectonic plate"],c:2,
   e:"Overgrazing is a leading human cause of desertification in the Sahel. When too many animals graze an area, vegetation is stripped faster than it can regenerate. With no plant roots to bind the soil, it becomes loose and vulnerable to wind and water erosion, degrading the land. Population growth increases pressure on the land, worsening the problem."},

  {q:"How does drip irrigation help address water scarcity in desert agricultural development?",
   opts:["It creates artificial rainfall by spraying water high into the atmosphere","It delivers water directly to plant roots through small pipes or tubes, minimising evaporation and waste","It channels river water into large open reservoirs for storage","It melts ice caps to create new freshwater supplies"],c:1,
   e:"Drip irrigation delivers water slowly and directly to the root zone of plants through a network of pipes and emitters. This dramatically reduces water lost to evaporation (which is very high in hot, dry conditions) and run-off. It can reduce agricultural water use by up to 50% compared to traditional surface irrigation, making it crucial for desert farming."},

  // Hard (Q9–10)
  {q:"Explain why a mesa eventually becomes a butte over geological time.",
   opts:["Tectonic uplift raises the mesa further until the base is exposed","A mesa forms when a hard rock cap is completely eroded away, leaving a flat plain. A butte forms earlier in this process","Continued lateral erosion of the resistant cap rock and underlying softer rock reduces the flat-topped mesa to a smaller, narrower column called a butte","Repeated flooding fills the mesa with sediment, compressing it into a butte"],c:2,
   e:"A mesa forms when a hard, resistant rock cap protects the softer rock beneath from erosion. Over time, the cap rock itself is gradually eroded at its edges by physical weathering and wind erosion, reducing its area. Eventually the mesa shrinks to a much narrower, isolated pillar called a butte. This is a classic sequence of desert erosion."},

  {q:"A geographer argues that the opportunities in hot desert environments outweigh the challenges. Evaluate this viewpoint.",
   opts:["This is completely correct — deserts have no challenges for development","This is completely wrong — no development is possible in deserts","This is debatable: whilst oil, solar energy and tourism present significant economic opportunities, extreme heat, water scarcity, remoteness and environmental fragility pose serious challenges that require expensive and careful management","Deserts are only challenging for farming, but all other industries thrive there"],c:2,
   e:"The question requires a balanced evaluation. Deserts offer substantial economic opportunities: oil wealth (Saudi Arabia, UAE), enormous solar energy potential, and growing tourism. However, the challenges are equally significant: extreme temperatures increase costs, water is critically scarce, infrastructure is expensive to build in remote areas, and development risks triggering desertification. A geographer would weigh these competing factors before reaching a judgement — neither an entirely optimistic nor entirely pessimistic view is accurate."}
],

"g8-08": [
  // Easy (Q1–4)
  {q:"Which natural resource has driven rapid economic development in the Gulf states of the Middle East?",
   opts:["Freshwater rivers","Tropical rainforests","Oil and natural gas","Gold and diamond mining"],c:2,
   e:"Oil and natural gas have been the primary driver of rapid economic development in Gulf states such as Saudi Arabia, the UAE, Kuwait and Qatar. The region holds approximately 48% of the world's proven oil reserves. Revenue from oil has funded infrastructure, healthcare, education and modernisation."},

  {q:"What is water scarcity?",
   opts:["A situation where a country has more water than it needs","A temporary shortage of water during summer months only","A situation where the demand for water exceeds the available supply of acceptable quality","The deliberate conservation of water in reservoirs"],c:2,
   e:"Water scarcity occurs when the demand for fresh water — for drinking, agriculture and industry — exceeds the available supply of water of acceptable quality. The Middle East is one of the most water-scarce regions on Earth, with many countries falling far below the UN threshold of 1,000 m³ of fresh water per person per year."},

  {q:"What is desalination?",
   opts:["The process of adding salt to water for industrial use","The removal of salt from seawater to produce fresh water","The purification of river water using sand filters","The collection of rainwater in underground reservoirs"],c:1,
   e:"Desalination is the process of removing dissolved salts and minerals from seawater to produce fresh water suitable for drinking or irrigation. Saudi Arabia has the world's largest desalination capacity and relies on it for the majority of its drinking water. However, the process is energy-intensive and expensive."},

  {q:"Which two major rivers flow through Iraq and were central to the ancient Mesopotamian civilisation?",
   opts:["The Nile and the Congo","The Tigris and the Euphrates","The Rhine and the Danube","The Jordan and the Litani"],c:1,
   e:"The Tigris and Euphrates rivers both originate in the mountains of Turkey and flow south-east through Syria and Iraq before reaching the Persian Gulf. The fertile land between them (Mesopotamia) was home to some of the world's earliest civilisations. Today both rivers are sources of geopolitical tension as Turkey controls upstream dams."},

  // Medium (Q5–8)
  {q:"Why does the UAE pursue economic diversification through tourism and finance rather than relying solely on oil income?",
   opts:["The UAE has already run out of oil reserves","Oil is infinitely renewable so the UAE is simply adding to existing income","Oil is a finite resource and global demand may fall as renewable energy grows; diversification reduces dependence on a single volatile commodity","The UAE government prefers tourism because it is cheaper to develop than oil extraction"],c:2,
   e:"Oil is a non-renewable resource — reserves will eventually be exhausted. Additionally, the global shift towards renewable energy threatens future demand for oil. Economic diversification (e.g. Dubai's focus on finance, aviation and tourism) reduces dependence on a single volatile commodity and creates a more resilient economy — a core aim of the UAE's development strategy."},

  {q:"How does the control of water resources in the Middle East contribute to political tension?",
   opts:["Countries argue about which country discovered water first","All Middle Eastern countries have equal access to water so there is no tension","Major rivers such as the Tigris, Euphrates and Jordan flow across international borders; upstream countries can reduce water flow downstream, causing disputes between nations competing for a scarce resource","Water is only used for drinking, so disagreements are minor and short-lived"],c:2,
   e:"Many of the Middle East's major rivers are transboundary — they cross international borders. Upstream countries can dam or divert rivers, reducing the flow that reaches downstream neighbours. For example, Turkey's dam construction on the Euphrates has reduced flow into Syria and Iraq. With water already scarce and demand rising, control of water sources is a significant source of political tension."},

  {q:"What is the 'resource curse' in relation to oil-rich countries?",
   opts:["Oil spills that damage agricultural land and reduce food production","Countries with large oil reserves always experience rapid, sustained and equitable development","The paradox whereby abundant natural resources can lead to economic instability, corruption, conflict and neglect of other sectors, often leaving the broader population poor despite national wealth","A situation where oil reserves run out unexpectedly quickly due to over-extraction"],c:2,
   e:"The 'resource curse' (also called the paradox of plenty) describes how countries with abundant natural resources can paradoxically experience poor economic growth, inequality and conflict. Revenue from oil can fuel corruption, undermine democratic institutions and create an economy that neglects other sectors. Wealth becomes concentrated in elite groups rather than distributed across society."},

  {q:"Describe one way in which colonial-era decisions continue to affect the modern Middle East.",
   opts:["Colonial powers invested heavily in schools and hospitals that still operate today","Colonial powers drew national boundaries that often divided ethnic, tribal and religious communities or merged rival groups into a single state, contributing to ongoing instability and conflict","Colonial powers introduced irrigation systems that solved the water scarcity problem","Colonial powers unified the region under a single stable government that is still in place"],c:1,
   e:"The Sykes-Picot Agreement (1916) between Britain and France divided the former Ottoman Empire into spheres of influence and drew borders largely for European strategic convenience, ignoring the ethnic, tribal and religious composition of local populations. These artificial borders placed rival groups within the same states and divided others across new national boundaries — a root cause of many ongoing regional conflicts."},

  // Hard (Q9–10)
  {q:"A student claims: 'Oil wealth has brought only benefits to the people of the Middle East.' Evaluate this claim.",
   opts:["The claim is entirely correct — all Middle Eastern countries are now wealthy and stable","The claim is entirely wrong — oil has brought no benefits whatsoever","The claim is too simplistic: oil wealth has funded impressive development in some Gulf states, but has also fuelled conflict, inequality, corruption and over-dependence on a single resource, with benefits distributed very unevenly across the region","The claim is correct only for countries with no oil reserves"],c:2,
   e:"A balanced evaluation recognises both sides. Oil wealth has funded remarkable development in Gulf states (infrastructure, healthcare, free education, modern cities). However, it has also fuelled geopolitical conflict over resources, entrenched authoritarian governance, created extreme inequality between and within states, and generated a 'resource curse' that discourages diversification. The benefits have not been shared equally — many people in oil-rich countries remain in poverty."},

  {q:"Evaluate virtual water trade as a strategy for managing water scarcity in the Middle East.",
   opts:["It is the most effective strategy because it completely solves water scarcity","It is irrelevant because the Middle East grows all its own food","It is a useful strategy — importing water-intensive crops rather than growing them locally effectively 'imports' the water used to produce them, reducing domestic water demand — but it creates food security risks through dependence on global food markets","It involves physically transporting water from Europe to the Middle East by tanker"],c:2,
   e:"Virtual water trade involves importing food products that require large amounts of water to produce (e.g. wheat, rice) rather than growing them domestically. This effectively 'imports' the water embedded in the food, reducing pressure on scarce local water supplies. It is a practical strategy for water-scarce countries. However, it increases dependence on global food markets and international relations, creating a potential food security vulnerability if trade is disrupted."}
],

"g8-09": [
  // Easy (Q1–4)
  {q:"At which type of plate boundary do most volcanoes and earthquakes occur?",
   opts:["Conservative (transform) boundaries only","Destructive (convergent) boundaries, where the most powerful tectonic activity occurs","Only in the middle of tectonic plates, far from boundaries","Only at constructive (divergent) boundaries"],c:1,
   e:"Most volcanic and earthquake activity is concentrated at destructive (convergent) plate boundaries, where an oceanic plate is subducted beneath a continental plate. The subduction process causes immense friction (triggering powerful earthquakes) and melts rock, which rises as magma to form volcanoes. This is why the Pacific Ring of Fire — a chain of subduction zones — is the world's most tectonically active zone."},

  {q:"What is the focus (hypocentre) of an earthquake?",
   opts:["The point on the Earth's surface directly above where the earthquake occurs","The instrument used to measure earthquake magnitude","The point inside the Earth where the earthquake originates and energy is released","The scale used to measure how much damage an earthquake causes"],c:2,
   e:"The focus (or hypocentre) is the point inside the Earth where the rupture and energy release of an earthquake originates. The epicentre is the point on the surface directly above the focus. Shallow-focus earthquakes (close to the surface) tend to cause more surface damage than deep-focus ones, because less energy is lost travelling through the Earth."},

  {q:"What sea surface temperature is required for a tropical storm to form?",
   opts:["Above 10°C","Above 20°C","Above 27°C","Above 35°C"],c:2,
   e:"Tropical storms require a sea surface temperature of at least 27°C to provide the warm, moist air needed to fuel the convection at the heart of the storm. As the warm ocean heats the air above it, the air rises rapidly, creating the low pressure and energy release that drives the storm system."},

  {q:"What is the 'eye' of a tropical storm?",
   opts:["The outer edge of the storm where the heaviest rainfall occurs","The calm, clear area of descending air at the centre of the storm, surrounded by the eyewall where the most violent winds occur","The instrument used to track the storm's path by satellite","The name given to the storm's point of landfall"],c:1,
   e:"The eye is a calm, cloud-free area of descending air at the very centre of a tropical storm, typically 30–65 km in diameter. It is surrounded by the eyewall — a ring of towering cumulonimbus clouds where the most intense winds, rainfall and storm surge occur. When the eye passes over an area there is a brief lull before the other side of the eyewall arrives."},

  // Medium (Q5–8)
  {q:"Explain why conservative (transform) plate boundaries can produce very powerful earthquakes despite no volcanic activity.",
   opts:["Plates collide head-on at conservative boundaries, creating enormous pressure and frequent eruptions","At conservative boundaries, plates move apart, leaving gaps that generate explosions","At conservative boundaries, plates slide past each other horizontally; crust is neither created nor destroyed, but enormous stress builds up over time and is released suddenly as very powerful, often shallow earthquakes","Conservative boundaries are always located deep in the ocean where no damage can occur"],c:2,
   e:"At a conservative (transform) boundary, two plates slide horizontally past each other. Because crust is neither created nor destroyed, there is no magma generation — hence no volcanoes. However, the plates do not move smoothly: they lock together and stress accumulates over decades or centuries. When this stress is suddenly released, the result is a powerful, shallow earthquake. The San Andreas Fault in California is the classic example."},

  {q:"Why does a tropical storm weaken when it moves over land?",
   opts:["The land is hotter than the ocean, so the storm gains more energy","The storm gains energy from friction with the landscape","The storm loses its energy source — warm, evaporating ocean water — and friction with the land surface also slows wind speeds","Governments use cloud-seeding to weaken approaching storms"],c:2,
   e:"Tropical storms are fuelled by warm, evaporating ocean water that provides the latent heat energy driving the storm's convection. When the storm moves over land, it loses this energy source and the warm ocean moisture that keeps it going. Additionally, friction with the rough land surface slows wind speeds. Without constant energy input from the warm ocean, the storm rapidly loses intensity and eventually dissipates."},

  {q:"Compare the primary and secondary effects of an earthquake.",
   opts:["Primary effects are long-term and secondary effects are immediate","Primary effects are the direct, immediate results of the earthquake itself (e.g. building collapse, ground rupture, deaths); secondary effects are the knock-on consequences that follow (e.g. fires from ruptured gas pipes, disease from contaminated water, economic disruption)","Primary effects only affect buildings; secondary effects only affect people","Both terms mean the same thing — all effects of an earthquake are equal"],c:1,
   e:"Primary (or direct) effects are the immediate physical consequences of the earthquake itself: ground shaking, building and bridge collapse, surface rupture, and the immediate deaths and injuries these cause. Secondary effects are the subsequent knock-on consequences: fires ignited by ruptured gas mains, tsunamis triggered by submarine earthquakes, disease outbreaks from contaminated water supplies, and long-term economic disruption."},

  {q:"Why is the Richter Scale no longer commonly used by seismologists?",
   opts:["It can only measure underwater earthquakes","It was only accurate for earthquakes in California and does not work elsewhere","It saturates (gives the same reading) for very large earthquakes and only measures surface waves, so the moment magnitude scale (Mw), which measures total energy released, is now preferred","It measures intensity of shaking felt at a location rather than the energy released at source"],c:2,
   e:"The Richter scale was developed by Charles Richter in 1935 for measuring local earthquakes in California using surface waves. It 'saturates' — meaning very large earthquakes all register around magnitude 8, making it impossible to distinguish their true size. The moment magnitude scale (Mw) measures the total energy released at the source and does not saturate, making it far more accurate for large earthquakes. Scientists now use Mw as the standard."},

  // Hard (Q9–10)
  {q:"Explain why the 2010 Haiti earthquake (magnitude 7.0) caused over 200,000 deaths, while the 2011 Christchurch earthquake (magnitude 6.3) caused 185 deaths.",
   opts:["The Haiti earthquake was far larger in magnitude, explaining the difference in deaths","The Christchurch earthquake struck a less populated area with no buildings","Haiti's status as a low-income country meant buildings were poorly constructed, emergency services were limited, and preparedness was low; Christchurch had earthquake-resistant buildings, well-resourced emergency services and extensive preparation — demonstrating that vulnerability, not just magnitude, determines death tolls","Both earthquakes were identical in impact; the death toll difference is a recording error"],c:2,
   e:"This question illustrates that the human impact of a hazard is not simply a function of its magnitude. Haiti is a low-income country where the majority of buildings were constructed without earthquake-resistant materials or techniques. Emergency services were severely under-resourced, and there was limited investment in preparation or early-warning systems. New Zealand (Christchurch) is a high-income country with enforced building codes, experienced emergency services and a culture of earthquake preparedness developed over decades. Vulnerability — shaped by income, governance and preparation — is the critical factor."},

  {q:"Evaluate the view that prediction is the most effective strategy for managing natural hazard risk.",
   opts:["Prediction is the only strategy needed — all other strategies are unnecessary once we can predict hazards","Prediction is completely ineffective because natural hazards are entirely random","Prediction is valuable but insufficient alone: accurate prediction saves lives by enabling evacuation, but it must be combined with land-use planning, hazard-resistant construction, community education and effective emergency response to be truly effective","Prediction only works for volcanic eruptions, not earthquakes or floods"],c:2,
   e:"Prediction (using seismometers, satellite monitoring, weather modelling) can provide vital early warnings that enable evacuation and preparation — as seen with successful volcano predictions in Iceland and typhoon warnings in the Philippines. However, prediction alone is insufficient: without the ability to act on warnings (e.g. evacuation routes, emergency services), communities remain vulnerable. Land-use planning, building regulations, community preparedness and rapid response are all essential components of effective hazard risk management."}
],

"g8-10": [
  // Easy (Q1–4)
  {q:"What does GIS stand for?",
   opts:["Global Irrigation System","Geographical Information System","Ground Investigation Survey","General Index of Statistics"],c:1,
   e:"GIS stands for Geographical Information System. It is a computer-based system that captures, stores, analyses and displays data linked to locations on the Earth's surface as layered digital maps, enabling geographers to identify spatial patterns and relationships."},

  {q:"A student measures the pebble sizes on a beach at five points: 4 cm, 7 cm, 3 cm, 7 cm, 9 cm. What is the mode?",
   opts:["4 cm","7 cm","9 cm","6 cm"],c:1,
   e:"The mode is the value that appears most frequently in a data set. In this data set (3, 4, 7, 7, 9) the value 7 cm appears twice — more than any other value. Therefore the mode is 7 cm. The mode is most useful for identifying the most common value when data contains repeats."},

  {q:"Which type of graph is most appropriate for showing how a city's population has changed over the last 100 years?",
   opts:["Pie chart","Bar chart","Line graph","Scatter graph"],c:2,
   e:"A line graph is the most appropriate chart for showing change over time (temporal data). The continuous line connecting data points emphasises the trend and allows the reader to see rates of change easily. A pie chart shows proportions, a bar chart compares discrete categories, and a scatter graph shows relationships between two variables."},

  {q:"What is the difference between primary and secondary data?",
   opts:["Primary data is more important than secondary data","Primary data is data you collect yourself first-hand in the field; secondary data is data collected by someone else that you then use in your investigation","Primary data always comes from books; secondary data comes from the internet","Primary data is only used in physical geography; secondary data is only used in human geography"],c:1,
   e:"Primary data is original data collected first-hand by the researcher — e.g. through questionnaires, field measurements or observations. Secondary data is pre-existing data collected by someone else — e.g. census figures, published maps, government statistics or previous research. Both types can be valuable; primary data is directly relevant to the investigation, while secondary data can provide context and historical comparison."},

  // Medium (Q5–8)
  {q:"A student records river velocities at six points: 0.3, 0.5, 0.8, 0.5, 1.2, 0.7 m/s. What is the mean velocity? (Round to 2 decimal places.)",
   opts:["0.50 m/s","0.67 m/s","0.55 m/s","0.80 m/s"],c:1,
   e:"Mean = sum of all values ÷ number of values. Sum = 0.3 + 0.5 + 0.8 + 0.5 + 1.2 + 0.7 = 4.0. Number of values = 6. Mean = 4.0 ÷ 6 = 0.667, which rounds to 0.67 m/s. Always check your arithmetic: add values carefully and divide by the total count of data points, not just the distinct values."},

  {q:"The same river velocity data is: 0.3, 0.5, 0.5, 0.7, 0.8, 1.2 m/s. What is the median?",
   opts:["0.50 m/s","0.60 m/s","0.70 m/s","0.55 m/s"],c:1,
   e:"When there is an even number of values, the median is the mean of the two middle values. Ordered data: 0.3, 0.5, 0.5, 0.7, 0.8, 1.2. The two middle values (3rd and 4th) are 0.5 and 0.7. Median = (0.5 + 0.7) ÷ 2 = 1.2 ÷ 2 = 0.60 m/s. The median is preferred over the mean when there are outliers, because an extreme value like 1.2 does not distort it."},

  {q:"Which sampling strategy involves dividing the study area into zones and collecting a proportional number of samples from each zone?",
   opts:["Random sampling","Systematic sampling","Stratified sampling","Convenience sampling"],c:2,
   e:"Stratified sampling divides the population or study area into sub-groups (strata) based on a relevant characteristic (e.g. land use zones, age groups) and then samples each stratum proportionally. This ensures all sub-groups are represented in the data. Random sampling uses chance to select sample points; systematic sampling uses regular intervals (e.g. every 10 metres along a transect)."},

  {q:"A geographer uses a scatter graph to plot GDP per capita against life expectancy for 30 countries. The points form a pattern rising from bottom-left to top-right. What does this show?",
   opts:["A negative correlation — as GDP increases, life expectancy decreases","No relationship between the two variables","A positive correlation — as GDP per capita increases, life expectancy tends to increase","The data is unreliable and should be discarded"],c:2,
   e:"A scatter graph that rises from bottom-left to top-right shows a positive correlation: as one variable increases, so does the other. In this case, countries with higher GDP per capita tend to have higher life expectancy — a well-established pattern in development geography. Note that correlation does not prove causation — a third factor (e.g. healthcare investment, which correlates with both GDP and life expectancy) may drive the relationship."},

  // Hard (Q9–10)
  {q:"A student investigating pebble size on a beach collects data only from one easily accessible point near the car park. What is the main limitation of this approach?",
   opts:["The student collected too many data points","Using a single, easily accessible location introduces sampling bias — the data may not represent the full beach, making conclusions unreliable and invalid","The student should have used secondary data instead","Pebble size cannot be measured accurately with a ruler"],c:1,
   e:"Sampling bias occurs when the method of data collection systematically favours certain locations, groups or values over others. Collecting data only from one convenient location (convenience sampling) means the sample is not representative of the whole beach. Pebble size typically changes along a beach (e.g. decreasing from headland to bay) and from the waterline to the back of the beach. A random or systematic sampling strategy would give more reliable, valid data."},

  {q:"In a fieldwork investigation, a student finds that their results do not support their original hypothesis. What should they do?",
   opts:["Discard the data and repeat the fieldwork until the results match the hypothesis","Change the hypothesis to match their results without mentioning the original prediction","Report the results honestly, explain why the hypothesis was not supported using geographical knowledge, evaluate potential sources of error in their methodology, and suggest improvements for future investigation","Ignore the anomalies and only include data that supports the hypothesis"],c:2,
   e:"Scientific and geographical enquiry requires honest reporting of results, even when they contradict the hypothesis. A student should report findings accurately, use geographical theory to explain why the expected pattern may not have occurred (e.g. localised factors, small sample size), evaluate the limitations and potential errors of their methodology (equipment accuracy, sample size, sampling bias), and suggest specific improvements. This demonstrates higher-order geographical thinking and is awarded the most marks in fieldwork write-ups."}
]

});

